      "id": "99211e75_0d06312d",
      "file_path": "models-interactions/model-impl/appclcm/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/appclcm/AppcLcmCommonHeader.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 37,
      "message": "@RequiredArgsConstructor only generates a constructor for final fields.  Since there are no final fields, it isn't needed.\n@NoArgsConstructor IS needed, because there's another constructor in the class and thus it wouldn't be available otherwise.  That's normal with java and not specific to lombok.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2019-10-24 21:41:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "0eb29b7f_ce3ad957",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "8699c759_771d876b",
      "file_path": "models-interactions/model-impl/appclcm/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/appclcm/AppcLcmCommonHeader.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 37,
      "message": "Fair point on the no args constructor, I can remove that. For required args, it works for fields that are not final if they are marked with @NonNull and are not initialized when they are declared. If you look in the AppcLcmCommonHeaderTest, I'm using a constructor that passes in originatorId, requestId, and subRequestId in which all those fields are marked as NonNull. I suppose this constructor isn't needed but it is nice to just pass in those fields when creating the object rather than creating the object and then calling three setter methods.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 1677,
        "name": "Daniel Cruz",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dc443y@att.com",
        "username": "dc443y"
      },
      "updated": "2019-10-24 22:13:51.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "99211e75_0d06312d",
      "unresolved": true
    },
